
[1]intend

   INTEND', v.t. [L. intendo; in and tendo, to stretch or strain, from
   teneo; Gr. to stretch.]

   1. To stretch; to strain; to extend; to distend.

   By this the lungs are intended or remitted.

                    [This literal sense is now uncommon.]

   2. To mean; to design; to purpose, that is, to stretch or set forward
   in mind. [This is now the usual sense.]

   For they intended evil against thee. Ps.21.

   3. To regard; to fix the mind on; to attend; to take care of.

   Having no children, she did with singular care and tenderness intend
   the education of Phillip.

   [This use of the word is now obsolete. We now use tend and superintend
                                 or regard.]

   4. To enforce; to make intense.
